,Recommended,550590,34918160,Posted: 13 September,all,Miathan,"Great puzzle game. As a kid, I was enchanted by one of these old light reflect games, in the early days of PC games when people ran MS-DOS. Archaica is like an evolved, modern version of that. The visuals are beautiful, the sound creates a nice ambiance and a magical feel to your actions. There are plenty of different puzzle pieces to influence light in many ways, from reflection and splitting to teleporting and refracting.There are two things that I find less good. The first is the story. It doesn't matter much, but if you're going to put a story in your game, make it fitting. This particular type of story is not one I would put in a puzzle game. It seems at odds with the atmosphere of the gameplay.Second: the difficulty. Maybe it's because I don't play puzzle games often, but this game is hard. I often find 4 or 5 near-solutions, where I could solve the puzzle if I could turn one mirror into another, or have one more tile of space. Sometimes after a long time of staring at variations of what I already made, I find the ""real"" solution, but sometimes I don't.There is a hint system, but it doesn't help with this. Knowing the location of a piece but not knowing which piece is supposed to go there barely reduces the difficulty at all. The only thing that worked for me is using the hint system to get all locations, but then it's suddenly very easy and just a matter of swapping stuff until it works. So instead, I've been using the solutions post on the Steam discussion forums when I really couldn't figure one out. Usually it's one small thing that I missed. For example, ""a color changing lens can be used to change the color of 2 orthogonal beams"". I had one puzzle all figured out except for that one fact. The hint system does nothing in that case, except funnel you into the right direction until by pure coincidence you stumble upon the solution.I think this game could benefit from a difficulty setting, where the current, single-solution game could be the highest difficulty, and one lower (medium) could give you a few extra tiles of space or an extra mirror here and there, to allow for secondary solutions for the non-hardcore puzzlers.Conclusion:Great game, as good as puzzle games get, as long as you don't care too much for story and don't mind a high difficulty."
